TI  - Politics and the International Lending Decisions of Banks
JO  - Journal of International Business Studies
SP  - 349
EP  - 359
VL  - 20
IS  - 2
AB  - It is widely believed that a country's foreign policy can influence the behavior of economic agents. We examine the extent to which political relationships between a bank's home country and a borrowing country affect the lending behavior of banks. Analysis of cooperative as well as conflictive events shows that banks consider mostly the former in their decision making process. The study points to a need for an interdisciplinary approach for explaining the international behavior of economic entities.
